---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import ProgressTimeline from "../../components/ProgressTimeline.astro";
import ArrowheadDemo from "../../components/ArrowheadDemo.tsx";

// The pilot as a chain of gates — each one cut, with controls, before the next.
const roadmap = [
  {
    date: "Jun 2026",
    phase: "Gate 0 · behaviour",
    title: "The model judges causal direction",
    summary:
      "Forward vs. reverse causal statements (“the storm caused the flood” and its reverse) separate cleanly — a coherence gap of +6.87 (95% CI [5.3, 8.5]) that holds across four content domains, two markers, and both clause orders, so it is not a connective or word-order artefact.",
    status: "done" as const,
  },
  {
    date: "Jun 2026",
    phase: "Gate 1 · probe",
    title: "Direction is encoded, and domain-general",
    summary:
      "A single linear direction in the residual stream decodes forward from reverse at 0.94 on a held-out domain (chance 0.5), peaking in the middle of the network (layer 12) — an abstract feature, not a memorised collocation.",
    status: "done" as const,
  },
  {
    date: "Jun 2026",
    phase: "Gate 2 · intervention",
    title: "Efficacious, but redundant",
    summary:
      "Steering along the direction moves the judgment monotonically; projecting it out — even across eleven layers, with bootstrap confidence intervals — does not. The direction is used, yet no single site is necessary: it is redundantly distributed.",
    status: "done" as const,
  },
  {
    date: "Jun 2026",
    phase: "Gate 3 · rich vs. lean",
    title: "Causal, not plausibility",
    summary:
      "On invented, zero-frequency relations fixed only by an in-context rule, the model still prefers the correct direction — and the direction learned from real data steers those novel judgments. So it tracks causal structure, not which sentence is more frequent.",
    status: "active" as const,
    color: "var(--accent-champagne)",
  },
  {
    date: "Planned",
    phase: "Next",
    title: "Is the redundancy structured?",
    summary:
      "Whether the redundant sites are the same across content domains — and, with the cross-lingual thesis question, across languages that mark causation differently.",
    status: "planned" as const,
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="Arrowhead · Xiaochuan Li"
  description="Arrowhead — an MSc-thesis pilot: does a real LLM hold a usable representation of causal direction, which event is the cause, and is it used? On Gemma-2-2B the direction is encoded, steerable, genuinely causal, yet redundantly distributed."
  showProgress={true}
  toc={true}
>
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Extension · mechanistic pilot · real LLM
    </div>
    <h1>Arrowhead — finding the cause inside the model</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      Does a model hold a representation of which event is the cause, and does it actually use it? An
      MSc-thesis pilot on Gemma-2-2B.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is the program's question — <em>does the model use the structure that licenses an inference,
      or a surface proxy that merely travels with it?</em> — narrowed to one sharp handle and pushed
      from behaviour into activation space. The handle, and the project's namesake, is
      <strong>causal direction</strong>: an association is a line, but a cause is a line with an
      <em>arrowhead</em> on it — and the arrowhead is what we go looking for inside the model. Given
      two events, which is the cause? Forward and reverse use almost the same words, so telling them
      apart cannot be lexical. And it is run on a real pretrained model (<strong>Gemma-2-2B</strong>),
      not the <a href="/research/mini-causal-models">MiniCausalLang</a> sandbox — making it the
      <a href="/research/sc-certification">Paper 1</a> intervention logic carried to the feature level.
    </p>

    <p>
      Following the program's discipline — fix the causal side, audit the model side, and only then
      claim — the pilot runs four gates and arrives at one compact picture:
    </p>

    <ProgressTimeline items={roadmap} accent="var(--accent-champagne)" />

    <h2>What the pilot found</h2>
    <p>One direction in the residual stream, characterised four ways:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Encoded</strong> — forward vs. reverse is linearly decodable, and it generalises to
        content domains held out of training (Gate 1).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Efficacious</strong> — steering along it moves the model's judgment monotonically; it is
        wired to the output, not a bystander (Gate 2).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Genuinely causal, not plausibility</strong> — it still works on invented, zero-frequency
        relations and transfers there from real data, so it tracks causal structure rather than surface
        frequency (Gate 3).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Redundant</strong> — yet projecting it out, even across eleven layers, does not remove
        the behaviour. It is used, but no single copy is load-bearing.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      "Used but not cleanly removable" is the empirical face of <strong>superposition</strong>: you can
      read the direction out, and still not cut it out. That turns a difficulty the program had only
      flagged in principle into something measured.
    </p>

    <p>
      Try it — steer the direction and the judgment moves; ablate it and, even across eleven layers,
      it barely does:
    </p>
    <ArrowheadDemo client:visible />

    <h2>Method — four gates</h2>
    <p>
      Each gate is one cut, with controls: a behavioural readout (does the model prefer the correct
      direction?), a linear probe with leave-one-domain-out evaluation (is it encoded, and general?),
      steering plus multi-layer ablation with bootstrap confidence intervals (is it used, and where?),
      and a frequency-neutral contrast (is it causal, or just plausible?). Forward and reverse are
      matched same-word minimal pairs; clause order and connective are counterbalanced so that neither
      can stand in for direction.
    </p>

    <h2>Relation to the rest of the work</h2>
    <p>
      This is the mechanistic step of the program, run on a real model: it takes the behavioural
      certification of <a href="/research/sc-certification">Stable Is Not Grounded</a> and asks whether
      the certified causal thing is a <em>used direction</em> in activation space — the same question as
      <a href="/research/latent-control-states">Latent Control States</a>, on a different handle. Its
      planned cross-lingual step — does the direction, and its redundancy, survive a change of
      language? — is where it meets the <a href="/research/typological-grounding">typological-grounding</a>
      frontier.
    </p>

    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)]">
      Status: a pilot, not a finished paper. Behaviour validated on the instruction-tuned model,
      mechanism on base Gemma-2-2B; one phenomenon, English, modest sample sizes, single runs (with
      bootstrap confidence intervals at the ablation stage). The "redundant" reading comes from
      projecting out a difference-of-means direction across a layer band; a subspace ablation would
      close it fully. Code, data, and full results — repository link to be added.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
